# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Aroll+ Mobile — environment configuration
# Copy this file to `.env` in the same folder and fill in your values.
# The `.env` file is git-ignored; never commit real secrets.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

# ── Android emulator → host machine (default) ────────────────────────────────
API_BASE_URL=http://10.0.2.2:8000/api/v1

# ── iOS simulator or desktop (macOS/Windows/Linux) ───────────────────────────
# API_BASE_URL=http://127.0.0.1:8000/api/v1

# ── Physical device (phone or tablet) ────────────────────────────────────────
# The device and your PC must be on the same Wi-Fi network.
# Replace the IP below with your PC's LAN IP (see "Finding your LAN IP" below).
#
# API_BASE_URL=http://192.168.1.42:8000/api/v1

# ── Google Maps (Android) ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Maps are configured at build time in android/local.properties (not this file).
# Copy android/local.properties.example → android/local.properties and set:
#   GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY=your_key
# Enable "Maps SDK for Android" for the same key used by admin-web
# (VITE_GOOGLE_MAPS_API_KEY).

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# PHYSICAL DEVICE SETUP — step by step
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# 1. FIND YOUR PC's LAN IP
#    Windows (PowerShell):
#      ipconfig | Select-String "IPv4"
#      → look for an address like 192.168.x.x or 10.x.x.x
#
#    macOS / Linux (Terminal):
#      ipconfig getifaddr en0      # macOS Wi-Fi
#      ip -4 addr show             # Linux
#
# 2. START THE BACKEND BOUND TO ALL INTERFACES
#    From the backend/ directory:
#      uvicorn app.main:app --host 0.0.0.0 --port 8000 --reload
#
#    "0.0.0.0" means the server accepts connections from any interface,
#    including your phone over Wi-Fi. Without this it only accepts localhost.
#
# 3. ALLOW PORT 8000 THROUGH YOUR FIREWALL
#    Windows (run PowerShell as Administrator):
#      netsh advfirewall firewall add rule `
#        name="Aroll+ Backend" protocol=TCP dir=in localport=8000 action=allow
#
#    macOS: System Settings → Network → Firewall → allow incoming on port 8000
#           (or disable the firewall temporarily while testing)
#
#    Linux (ufw):
#      sudo ufw allow 8000/tcp
#
# 4. VERIFY connectivity from the phone (optional but recommended)
#    Open a browser on the device and visit:
#      http://<YOUR_PC_LAN_IP>:8000/docs
#    You should see the FastAPI Swagger UI.
#
# 5. SET API_BASE_URL IN YOUR .env
#    Uncomment the physical-device line above and replace the IP, e.g.:
#      API_BASE_URL=http://192.168.1.42:8000/api/v1
#
# 6. RUN THE APP
#      flutter run                    # picks up the device automatically
#      flutter run -d <device-id>    # target a specific device
#
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# TROUBLESHOOTING
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# • "Connection refused" or timeout → firewall not open, or backend not on 0.0.0.0
# • Wrong IP → your router may assign a new IP after reconnect; recheck with step 1
# • HTTP blocked on Android → android:usesCleartextTraffic="true" is set in
#   android/app/src/debug/AndroidManifest.xml (debug builds only; release is unaffected)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
